  "items": [
    {
      "type": "concept",
      "content_latex": "Prime factorisation examples:\n\n$30 = 2 \\times 3 \\times 5$\n\n$45 = 3 \\times 3 \\times 5$",
      "source_images": ["image305.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "definition",
      "content_latex": "Common factors are numbers that are factors of two or more numbers.\n\nThe highest common factor or HCF of the numbers is the largest factor that is common to all of them.",
      "source_images": ["image306.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Find the highest common factor of:\n\n(a) $8a$ and $12b$\n\n(b) $4x^2$ and $6xy$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $8a = 2 \\times 2 \\times 2 \\times a$\n\n$12b = 2 \\times 2 \\times 3 \\times b$\n\n$\\therefore$ HCF $= 2 \\times 2 = 4$\n\n(b) $4x^2 = 2 \\times 2 \\times x \\times x$\n\n$6xy = 2 \\times 3 \\times x \\times y$\n\n$\\therefore$ HCF $= 2 \\times x = 2x$",
      "source_images": ["image307.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 3\n\nFind the HCF of $3(x + 3)$ and $(x + 3)(x + 1)$.\n\n$3(x + 3) = 3 \\times (x + 3)$\n\n$(x + 3)(x + 1) = (x + 3) \\times (x + 1)$\n\n$\\therefore$ HCF $= (x + 3)$",
      "source_images": ["image308.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "definition",
      "content_latex": "Factorisation is the process of writing an expression as a product of its factors.\n\nFactorisation is the reverse process of expansion.",
      "source_images": ["image309.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "concept",
      "content_latex": "In expansion: $5(x - 1) = 5x - 5$\n\nIn factorisation: $5x - 5 = 5(x - 1)$",
      "source_images": ["image310.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "concept",
      "content_latex": "FACTORISING FULLY\n\nConsider the expression $8x + 4 = 2(4x + 2)$. This expression is not fully factorised since $(4x + 2)$ still has a common factor of 2 which could be removed. So, although 2 was a common factor, it was not the HCF. The HCF is 4 and so\n\n$8x + 4 = 4(2x + 1)$ is fully factorised.",
      "source_images": ["image311.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 4\n\nFully factorise:\n\n(a) $3a + 6$\n\n(b) $ab - 2bc$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $3a + 6$\n$= 3 \\times a + 3 \\times 2$\n$= 3(a + 2)$ {HCF is 3}\n\n(b) $ab - 2bc$\n$= a \\times b - 2 \\times b \\times c$\n$= b(a - 2c)$ {HCF is $b$}",
      "source_images": ["image311.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 5\n\nFully factorise:\n\n(a) $8x^2 + 12x$\n\n(b) $3y^2 - 6xy$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $8x^2 + 12x$\n$= 2 \\times 4 \\times x \\times x + 3 \\times 4 \\times x$\n$= 4x(2x + 3)$ {HCF is $4x$}\n\n(b) $3y^2 - 6xy$\n$= 3 \\times y \\times y - 2 \\times 3 \\times x \\times y$\n$= 3y(y - 2x)$ {HCF is $3y$}",
      "source_images": ["image312.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 6\n\nFully factorise: $-2a + 6ab$\n\n$-2a + 6ab$\n$= 6ab - 2a$ {Rewrite with $6ab$ first.}\n$= 2 \\times 3 \\times a \\times b - 2 \\times a$\n$= 2a(3b - 1)$ {as $2a$ is the HCF}",
      "source_images": ["image313.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 7\n\nFully factorise: $-2x^2 - 4x$\n\n$-2x^2 - 4x$\n$= -2 \\times x \\times x + -2 \\times 2 \\times x$\n$= -2x(x + 2)$ {as HCF is $-2x$}",
      "source_images": ["image314.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 8\n\nFully factorise:\n\n(a) $2(x + 3) + x(x + 3)$\n\n(b) $x(x + 4) - (x + 4)$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $2(x + 3) + x(x + 3)$ {HCF $= (x + 3)$}\n$= (x + 3)(2 + x)$\n\n(b) $x(x + 4) - (x + 4)$ {HCF $= (x + 4)$}\n$= x(x + 4) - 1(x + 4)$\n$= (x + 4)(x - 1)$",
      "source_images": ["image315.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 9\n\nFully factorise $(x - 1)(x + 2) + 3(x - 1)$\n\n$(x - 1)(x + 2) + 3(x - 1)$ {HCF $= (x - 1)$}\n$= (x - 1)[(x + 2) + 3]$\n$= (x - 1)(x + 5)$",
      "source_images": ["image316.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "concept",
      "content_latex": "DIFFERENCE OF TWO SQUARES FACTORISATION\n\n$a^2 - b^2 = (a + b)(a - b)$",
      "source_images": ["image317.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 10\n\nFully factorise:\n\n(a) $x^2 - 4$\n\n(b) $1 - 25y^2$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $x^2 - 4$\n$= x^2 - 2^2$\n$= (x + 2)(x - 2)$\n\n(b) $1 - 25y^2$\n$= 1^2 - (5y)^2$\n$= (1 + 5y)(1 - 5y)$",
      "source_images": ["image318.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 11\n\nFully factorise:\n\n(a) $2x^2 - 18$\n\n(b) $x^3 - xy^2$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $2x^2 - 18$\n$= 2(x^2 - 9)$\n$= 2(x + 3)(x - 3)$\n\n(b) $x^3 - xy^2$\n$= x(x^2 - y^2)$\n$= x(x + y)(x - y)$",
      "source_images": ["image319.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 12\n\nFully factorise:\n\n(a) $4a^2 - 9b^2$\n\n(b) $x^2y^2 - 16$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $4a^2 - 9b^2$\n$= (2a)^2 - (3b)^2$\n$= (2a + 3b)(2a - 3b)$\n\n(b) $x^2y^2 - 16$\n$= (xy)^2 - 4^2$\n$= (xy + 4)(xy - 4)$",
      "source_images": ["image320.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 13\n\nFully factorise:\n\n(a) $(x + 2)^2 - 9$\n\n(b) $25 - (x - 2)^2$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $(x + 2)^2 - 9$\n$= (x + 2)^2 - 3^2$\n$= [(x + 2) + 3][(x + 2) - 3]$\n$= [x + 2 + 3][x + 2 - 3]$\n$= (x + 5)(x - 1)$\n\n(b) $25 - (x - 2)^2$\n$= 5^2 - (x - 2)^2$\n$= [5 + (x - 2)][5 - (x - 2)]$\n$= [5 + x - 2][5 - x + 2]$\n$= (x + 3)(7 - x)$",
      "source_images": ["image321.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "concept",
      "content_latex": "PERFECT SQUARE FACTORISATION\n\n$a^2 + 2ab + b^2 = (a + b)^2$ and $a^2 - 2ab + b^2 = (a - b)^2$",
      "source_images": ["image323.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 14\n\nFind all perfect squares of the form:\n\n(a) $x^2 + \\square + 25$\n\n(b) $4x^2 + \\square + 9$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $x^2 + \\square + 25 = x^2 + \\square + 5^2$\n\nThis is of the form $(a + b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2$ with $a = x$ and $b = \\pm 5$.\n\n$\\therefore$ $2ab = 2 \\times x \\times \\pm 5 = \\pm 10x$\n\n$\\therefore$ the perfect squares are $x^2 + 10x + 25$ and $x^2 - 10x + 25$.\n\n(b) $4x^2 + \\square + 9 = (2x)^2 + \\square + 3^2$\n\nThis is of the form $(a + b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2$ with $a = 2x$ and $b = \\pm 3$.\n\n$\\therefore$ $2ab = 2 \\times 2x \\times \\pm 3 = \\pm 12x$\n\n$\\therefore$ the perfect squares are $4x^2 + 12x + 9$ and $4x^2 - 12x + 9$.",
      "source_images": ["image324.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 15\n\nFactorise:\n\n(a) $x^2 + 20x + 100$\n\n(b) $x^2 - 8x + 16$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $x^2 + 20x + 100$\n$= x^2 + 2 \\times x \\times 10 + 10^2$\n$= (x + 10)^2$\n\n(b) $x^2 - 8x + 16$\n$= x^2 - 2 \\times x \\times 4 + 4^2$\n$= (x - 4)^2$",
      "source_images": ["image325.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 16\n\nFactorise:\n\n(a) $16x^2 + 24x + 9$\n\n(b) $4x^2 - 20x + 25$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $16x^2 + 24x + 9$\n$= (4x)^2 + 2 \\times 4x \\times 3 + 3^2$\n$= (4x + 3)^2$\n\n(b) $4x^2 - 20x + 25$\n$= (2x)^2 - 2 \\times 2x \\times 5 + 5^2$\n$= (2x - 5)^2$",
      "source_images": ["image326.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 17\n\nFully factorise:\n\n(a) $3x^2 - 18x + 27$\n\n(b) $-2x^2 + 8x - 8$\n\nSolutions:\n\n(a) $3x^2 - 18x + 27$\n$= 3(x^2 - 6x + 9)$\n$= 3(x^2 - 2 \\times x \\times 3 + 3^2)$\n$= 3(x - 3)^2$\n\n(b) $-2x^2 + 8x - 8$\n$= -2(x^2 - 4x + 4)$\n$= -2(x^2 - 2 \\times x \\times 2 + 2^2)$\n$= -2(x - 2)^2$",
      "source_images": ["image327.png"]
